{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 21:01:17.103122", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope\\n- Detect anomalies\\n- Localize faulty devices\\n- Identify likely root cause\\n- No remediation proposed\\n\\nSummary of Network Health\\n- IP reachability across hosts, servers, and load balancer is generally healthy. Broad ping tests show 0% packet loss and low RTTs across the topology, indicating OSPF routing is functioning end-to-end.\\n- DNS resolution is working; name lookup times in curl traces are low (milliseconds), and DNS server is reachable.\\n- HTTP application layer: Most services respond normally (web0.local, web2.local, web3.local, web99.local). One service (web1.local) consistently times out.\\n\\nKey Findings and Evidence\\n1) End-to-end connectivity\\n- From multiple sources (hosts, servers), pings to 10.200.0.0/24 nodes (dns_server, load_balancer, web_server_0..3) succeed with 0% loss.\\n- Minor jitter spikes observed from host_2_1_1_1 to some server IPs (up to ~20 ms); not indicative of a reachability problem.\\n\\n2) HTTP service checks from hosts\\n- host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - http://web0.local, web2.local, web3.local: successful (total ~1–2 s)\\n  - http://web99.local (load balancer): successful (total ~1.03–1.07 s)\\n  - http://web1.local: all attempts timed out (>10 s)\\n- host_2_1_1_1:\\n  - Same pattern: web0/2/3 and web99 successful; web1 timed out in all trials.\\n\\n3) Direct IP HTTP checks to web_server_1 (10.200.0.4)\\n- From host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1: curl to http://10.200.0.4 timed out (>10 s).\\n- From dns_server: curl to http://10.200.0.4 timed out (>10 s).\\n- From web_server_1 itself:\\n  - curl to http://127.0.0.1 and http://10.200.0.4 also timed out (>10 s).\\n\\n4) Service/process state on web_server_1\\n- netstat on web_server_1 shows:\\n  - TCP 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN handled by PID 44/python3 (not Apache)\\n  - Established local loopback connection 127.0.0.1:34214 → 127.0.0.1:80, with Recv-Q 73 on server side (data queued/not being read) indicating the HTTP server process is not responding correctly.\\n  - Connection from 10.200.0.2 (dns_server) to 10.200.0.4:80 established, but application still not completing responses (corroborates curl timeouts).\\n- apache2 service on web_server_1: inactive (dead).\\n- apache2 on web_server_0/2/3: also shown as inactive in systemd, but those hosts are serving HTTP successfully (implies they may also be running a non-Apache HTTP server that responds correctly). The issue is specific to web_server_1’s running process.\\n\\nAnomalies Detected\\n- Complete HTTP application outage for web1.local (10.200.0.4) from all tested sources, including locally on the server itself.\\n- On web_server_1, a python3 process is bound to port 80 and appears hung/unresponsive (backlog/Recv-Q buildup and consistent curl timeouts).\\n- Apache (apache2) is not the active web server on web_server_1; it is inactive.\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- Device: web_server_1 (10.200.0.4)\\n- Layer: Application layer (HTTP service on TCP/80)\\n- Network transport/connectivity is not the cause (pings succeed, TCP sessions establish). The fault is confined to the HTTP server process on web_server_1.\\n\\nLikely Root Cause\\n- Misconfiguration or failure/hang of the Python-based HTTP service running on port 80 on web_server_1, resulting in unresponsive behavior to both local and remote HTTP requests.\\n- The Apache service is inactive; given naming conventions (web1.local intended as Apache), the presence of a python3-bound listener suggests an incorrect service deployed or a failed replacement, causing web1.local to be unavailable.\\n\\nImpact Assessment\\n- Users cannot access the web1.local service (application outage).\\n- Other web services (web0/local, web2/local, web3/local) and the Nginx load balancer at web99.local are reachable and perform normally.\\n- No evidence of OSPF routing faults, DNS failures, or general network transport issues.\\n\\nEnd of report., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bf7b517d-79a4-44f1-b76d-e00c854f8336'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
